# Stage 10 — Column-Level Lineage

## Goal
Zoom in below the Dataset level. Track exactly **which column in an input dataset feeds which column in an output dataset**, through a specific job. Answers: *"If I rename `orders.customer_id`, what downstream columns break?"*

## Background — The OpenLineage Column Lineage Facet

OpenLineage already has a `columnLineage` facet in the output dataset's `facets` object. The structure is:

```json
{
  "outputs": [{
    "namespace": "postgres",
    "name": "orders",
    "facets": {
      "columnLineage": {
        "fields": {
          "customer_id": {
            "inputFields": [
              { "namespace": "postgres", "name": "raw_orders", "field": "cust_id" }
            ]
          },
          "total_amount": {
            "inputFields": [
              { "namespace": "postgres", "name": "raw_payments", "field": "amount" }
            ]
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }]
}
```

We already have `facets: dict[str, Any]` on `OLDataset` — the data is already coming in. We just need to extract it.

---

## New Neo4j Graph Schema (additions only)

```
EXISTING (unchanged):
(:Dataset)-[:CONSUMES]->(:Job)
(:Job)-[:PRODUCES]->(:Dataset)

NEW additions:
(:Column { uri, name, dataset_uri })
(:Column)-[:COLUMN_OF]->(:Dataset)
(:Column)-[:TRANSFORMS { via_job, run_id, timestamp }]->(:Column)
```

### Column Node Properties
| Property | Type | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `uri` | string (unique key) | `"postgres://orders/customer_id"` |
| `name` | string | `"customer_id"` |
| `dataset_uri` | string (FK to Dataset) | `"postgres://orders"` |

### Column URI Format
`{dataset_namespace}://{dataset_name}/{column_name}`

Example: `postgres://raw_orders/cust_id`

### New Constraints to create at startup
```cypher
CREATE CONSTRAINT column_uri_unique IF NOT EXISTS
FOR (c:Column) REQUIRE c.uri IS UNIQUE;

CREATE INDEX column_dataset_index IF NOT EXISTS
FOR (c:Column) ON (c.dataset_uri);
```

